1. abavus tuus: Augustus. Nero’s mother, Agrippina Minor, was the daughter of Agrippina Major, who was the daughter of Augustus's daughter Julia. By adoption the relation could also be traced through the emperor Tiberius and his adopted son Germanicus, who was the father of Agrippina Minor. —si non ignovisset, etc.: Cicero hints at the same thing in reference to Julius Caesar in the Pro sslarcello, v. 13: amplissimos viros . . . patriae reddidit. — Sallustium: C. Sallustius Crispus, grandson of the sister of Sallust the historian, and his heir, was at first an opponent of Augustus, but afterwards became influential as his friend. His gardens near the Porta Collina were famous. Horace addressed to him Germ. ii. 2. —Cocceiosx M.
